      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Perhaps Republicans have a suggestion for the global warming problem (letters, Aug. 6): Shrink the Federal Government and let towns and states handle weather-related relief for flooding, droughts and tornadoes using commercial insurance.</p>
        <p>If local budgets handled such costs, global weather changes would get serious attention. And since insurance companies must use good science in assessing risk factors or go under, we would be more likely to get accurate statistics, rather than hype, on the actual rate of global warming.</p>
        <p>LAURIE ACTON  Hartland, Vt., Aug. 6, 1999</p>
      </block>
